<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06042k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06042k">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06042k"> 42(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> drum call heed to self</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;Jouer pour l&apos;enfant, &hellip; c&apos;est souvent se mettre en avant, afficher sa superiorit&eacute;, faire preuve de force, attester enfin sa personnalit&eacute;. S&apos;il aime les amusements bruyants et tapageurs, par exemple, <mark>le tambour</mark>, ce n&apos;est pas pr&eacute;cis&eacute;ment que son oreille soit charm&eacute;e de tout de fracas; c&apos;est que, par le bruit qu&apos;il fait, <mark>il appelle l&apos;attention sur lui</mark>, se signale et se fait remarquer.&rdquo; <font color="green">[Playing for the child, ... is often to put forward, to show his superiority, to show strength, to finally attest his personality. If he likes noisy and boisterous amusements, for example, the drum, it is not exactly that his ear is charmed with all the noise; it is because, by the noise he makes, he draws attention to himself, points out himself, and points himself out.]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 54-5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
